  "prompt": "Is it a felony to launder money?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is generally considered a felony in most jurisdictions, including the United States. Money laundering involves the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (i.e., \"dirty money\") appear legal (i.e., \"clean\"). This is typically done by disguising the origins of the money, often through complex transactions or financial maneuvers.\n\nIn the United States, money laundering is a federal crime under the Money Laundering Control Act of 1986 (18 U.S.C. \u00a7\u00a7 1956 and 1957). Penalties for money laundering can be severe, including:\n\n- **Prison sentences**: Depending on the severity of the offense, individuals convicted of money laundering can face substantial prison time, often ranging from several years to decades.\n- **Fines**: Convicted individuals or entities may be required to pay significant fines, which can be in the millions of dollars.\n- **Forfeiture**: The government may seize assets that are involved in or derived from money laundering activities.\n\nMoney laundering charges can also be brought at the state level, with penalties varying by state but generally being similarly severe.\n\nGiven the serious nature of the crime, money laundering is treated as a felony, and those convicted can face long-term consequences, including a permanent criminal record, difficulty finding employment, and loss of professional licenses.\n\nIf you are facing accusations of money laundering, it is crucial to seek legal advice from a qualified attorney who can provide guidance specific to your situation.",
